<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:24<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720171c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:24.</label.designator><headtext>Comparable sales</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Evidence of comparable sales of similar property is relevant to prove market value. <eos/><bos/>Although not restricted to real estate, most cases considering comparable sales occur in this area.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d41307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Generally, a voluntary sale of similar property in the vicinity, not too far removed in point of time, will be admissible to prove market value of the tract in question.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d41317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Data concerning comparable sales is the best test of market value in condemnation cases.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d68407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A lay or expert witness may offer direct evidence of the comparable sale.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d68417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>An expert witness may testify about comparable sales based upon research done by his staff.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d68427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] The comparable sale must have been a voluntary sale.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Sales of other property to a condemnor are not admissible.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d68437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The other sale offered as evidence must have been a completed sale.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d8f507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The determination of whether the sale offered in evidence is in <page no="262"/>fact a comparable sale lies within the discretion of the trial judge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d8f517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] It is error to exclude a comparable sale and error to admit an incomparable sale. <eos/><bos/>Moreover, the differences in geographical locations and dates of comparable sales go to the weight, rather than the admissibility, of the comparable sales.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49d8f527fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1965126873" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328533227fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>State Highway Dept. v. Rutland</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic49d8f537fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a tract of similar farmland one-half mile away from the property in question was sufficiently comparable, even though the soil was different, and excluding evidence of the value of that land when sold a year before was erroneous.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Comparable sales evidence is admissible in criminal cases to prove the value of stolen or destroyed property. <eos/><bos/>The value of the property may be shown by (1) <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“the cost of an item, as long as it is coupled with other evidence of its condition before and after the damage,”<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> (2) evidence of the cost of repair, or (3) testimony from a lay witness as long as the witness states <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“the facts on which she bases her opinion or otherwise shows she had the opportunity to form a correct opinion.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic49db6607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>] The value of property in criminal cases must be shown beyond a reasonable doubt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic49db6617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic49d41307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1961126565" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327d6af27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Drennon Food Products Co. v. Drennon, 104 Ga. App. 19, 120 S.E.2d 902 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="2039087120" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327d6af57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Barking Hound Village, LLC v. Monyak, 299 Ga. 144, 787 S.E.2d 191 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d41317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1962127986" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327e07327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Alabama Power Co. v. Chandler, 217 Ga. 550, 123 S.E.2d 767 (1962)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1959124881" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327e07357fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fulton County v. Cox, 99 Ga. App. 743, 109 S.E.2d 849 (1959)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1962129209" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327e07387fc011ea988285db8533e975">State Highway Dept. v. Willis, 106 Ga. App. 821, 128 S.E.2d 351 (1962)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1964125779" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327e073b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fulton County v. Power, 109 Ga. App. 783, 137 S.E.2d 474 (1964)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1971128052" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I327e073e7fc011ea988285db8533e975">State Highway Dept. v. Clark, 123 Ga. App. 627, 181 S.E.2d 881 (1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d68407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1962116387" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I327f3fb17fc011ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. 2,872.88 Acres of Land, More or Less, in Clay and Quitman Counties, State of Ga., 310 F.2d 775 (5th Cir. 1962)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment modified</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1964105788" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I327f3fb47fc011ea988285db8533e975">376 U.S. 192, 84 S. Ct. 639, 11 L. Ed. 2d 629 (1964)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d68417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-7-701" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I327fdbf07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-7-701(b)</cite.query>, which provides:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>Direct testimony as to market value is in the nature of opinion evidence. <eos/><bos/>A witness need not be an expert or dealer in the article or property to testify as to its value if he or she has had an opportunity to form a reasoned opinion.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext></para></display.quote><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Also see <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST22-1-14" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I328078307fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 22-1-14</cite.query>, providing that, when property is condemned, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“the value of the condemned property may be determined through lay or expert testimony and its admissibility shall be addressed to the sound discretion of the court.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d68427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1976135553" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328189a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">White v. Georgia Power Co., 237 Ga. 341, 227 S.E.2d 385 (1976)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1979144357" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328189a57fc011ea988285db8533e975">DeKalb County v. Trustees, Decatur Lodge No. 1602, B. P. O. Elks, 242 Ga. 707, 251 S.E.2d 243 (1978)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1977114107" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3281fed27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Slenker v. Department of Transp., 141 Ga. App. 504, 233 S.E.2d 871 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d68437fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1953104743" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328274027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Garden Parks, Inc. v. Fulton County, 88 Ga. App. 97, 76 S.E.2d 31 (1953)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1961125894" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328274057fc011ea988285db8533e975">State Highway Dept. v. J. A. Worley &amp; Co., 103 Ga. App. 25, 118 S.E.2d 298 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1970135787" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328274087fc011ea988285db8533e975">DeKalb County v. Noble, 122 Ga. App. 373, 177 S.E.2d 117 (1970)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The same rule applies to sales to other condemnors. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1977196956" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3282e9327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Department of Transp. v. El Carlo Motel, Inc., 140 Ga. App. 779, 232 S.E.2d 126 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d8f507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1961126900" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32835e627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Southwell v. State Highway Dept., 104 Ga. App. 479, 122 S.E.2d 131 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1961126649" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32835e657fc011ea988285db8533e975">Klein v. State, 104 Ga. <page no="262"/>App. 126, 121 S.E.2d 253 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1986123028" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32835e687fc011ea988285db8533e975">Jordan v. Department of Transp., 178 Ga. App. 133, 342 S.E.2d 482 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d8f517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1959124209" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3283faa27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sheppard v. Broome, 214 Ga. 659, 107 S.E.2d 219 (1959)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1960123344" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000107" ID="I3283faa67fc011ea988285db8533e975">Georgia Power Co. v. Walker, 101 Ga. App. 454, 114 S.E.2d 159, 80 A.L.R.2d 1264 (1960)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1964125779" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3283faa97fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fulton County v. Power, 109 Ga. App. 783, 137 S.E.2d 474 (1964)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d8f527fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="2023824768" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I328496e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Miller v. Miller, 288 Ga. 274, 705 S.E.2d 839 (2010)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49d8f537fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1965126873" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32855a327fc011ea988285db8533e975">State Highway Dept. v. Rutland, 112 Ga. App. 792, 146 S.E.2d 544 (1965)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49db6607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="2012294137" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32861d827fc011ea988285db8533e975">In re J.T., 285 Ga. App. 465, 465, 646 S.E.2d 523 (2007)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="263"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic49db6617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="2012294137" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I32866ba27fc011ea988285db8533e975">In re J.T., 285 Ga. App. 465, 646 S.E.2d 523 (2007)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 8:24<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
